<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	U. S. Credit Agreement
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On November&nbsp;6, 2013, the Company entered into the U.S. Credit Agreement (Credit Agreement) which provides for a senior unsecured revolving credit facility (Revolver) in an amount up to $225.0 million which was originally set to expire on November&nbsp;6, 2018. &#160;On November&nbsp;6, 2014, an amendment was signed to the Credit Agreement in order to extend the expiration date for one additional year and to release certain guarantors under the Credit Agreement that have nominal value.&#160;
</FONT>
	On November&nbsp;6, 2015, an additional amendment was signed which extends the Revolver for an additional one-year period to November&nbsp;6, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
	A portion of the Revolver not in excess of $75.0 million shall be available for standby or letters of credit for trade, $15.0 million shall be available for swing loans, and $50.0 million shall be available for loans or letters of credit in certain foreign denominated currencies.&#160; The Company may have the option to increase the Revolver in an amount not to exceed $75.0 million with the consent of the Lenders.&#160; Availability under the Revolver is conditioned upon various customary conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Credit Agreement also provides for senior unsecured delayed draw term loans (Delayed Draw Term Loans) in an aggregate amount up to $75.0 million which expire on November&nbsp;6, 2020.&#160;
</FONT>
	The full amount of the Delayed Draw Term Loans is outstanding as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Beginning January&nbsp;1, 2016, quarterly repayments are required equal to 2.5% of the outstanding balance of the Delayed Draw Term Loans, with the remaining balance due on the November&nbsp;6, 2020 expiration date.&nbsp; As a result, as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, $7.5 million is shown as current portion of long-term debt within the consolidated balance sheet.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Upon entering into the Credit Agreement, the Company incurred issuance costs of $0.8 million which were deferred and are being amortized over the term of the Revolver and Delayed Draw Term Loan facilities.&#160; A quarterly nonrefundable commitment fee is payable by the Company based on the unused availability under the Revolver and the undrawn portion of the Delayed Draw Term Loans and is currently equal to 0.15%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The interest rate on amounts owed under the&nbsp;Revolver and Delayed Draw Term Loans&nbsp;will be, at the Company&#146;s option, either (i)&nbsp;a fluctuating Base Rate or (ii)&nbsp;an adjusted LIBOR rate plus in each case, an applicable margin based on the Company&#146;s leverage ratio as set forth in the Credit Agreement.&#160; The interest rate charged on amounts owed under swing loans will be either (i)&nbsp;a fluctuating
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23432_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Base Rate or (ii)&nbsp;such other interest rates as the lender and the Company may agree to from time to time.&#160; The interest rate per annum on outstanding borrowings ranged from 1.25% to 1.40% as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, and 1.17% to 1.31% as of December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:22.5PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Total outstanding borrowings under the Revolver were $32.7 million and $21.7 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&#160; Total availability under the Revolver as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 was $189.9 million and $201.1 million, respectively, after considering borrowings and outstanding letters of credit of $2.4 million and $2.2 million, respectively.&#160; Total outstanding borrowings under the Delayed Draw Term Loan were $75.0 million and $45.0 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&#160; Total availability under the Delayed Draw Term Loan as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 was zero and $30.0 million, respectively.&#160; The outstanding borrowings are shown as current portion of long-term debt and long-term debt within the consolidated balance sheets.&#160; Borrowings and repayments are presented on a gross basis within the Company&#146;s consolidated statement of cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Certain of the Company&#146;s domestic subsidiaries unconditionally guarantee all indebtedness and obligations related to borrowings under the Credit Agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#146;s obligations under the Credit Agreement are unsecured.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Credit Agreement contains customary affirmative and negative covenants for credit facilities of this type.&#160; The Company is permitted to pay dividends so long as the sum of availability under the Credit Agreement and the amount of U.S. cash on hand is at least $50.0 million, and debt is less than or equal to 2.75x earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization.&#160; In addition, the Credit Agreement includes limitations on the Company and its subsidiaries with respect to indebtedness, additional liens, disposition of assets or subsidiaries, and transactions with affiliates.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company must comply with certain financial covenants including a minimum interest coverage ratio and a maximum leverage ratio as defined within the Credit Agreement. The Company was in compliance with all such covenants as of December 31, 2015.&#160; The Credit Agreement also provides for customary events of default, including failure to pay principal or interest when due, breach of representations and warranties, certain insolvency or receivership events affecting the Company and its subsidiaries and a change in control of the Company.&nbsp;&nbsp;If an event of default occurs, the lenders will be under no further obligations to make loans or issue letters of credit.&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon the occurrence of certain events of default, all outstanding obligations of the Company automatically will become immediately due and payable, and other events of default will allow the agent to declare all or any portion of the outstanding obligations of the Company to be immediately due and payable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Japanese Loans
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Calgon Carbon Japan (CCJ) maintains a Term Loan Agreement (Japanese Term Loan) and a Working Capital Loan Agreement (Japanese Working Capital Loan).&#160; The Company is jointly and severally liable as the guarantor of CCJ&#146;s obligations and the Company permitted CCJ to grant a security interest and continuing lien in certain of its assets, including inventory and accounts receivable, to secure its obligations under both loan agreements. The amount of the assets available to be pledged is in excess of the outstanding obligation as of December 31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Japanese Term Loan provides for a principal amount of 1.0 billion Japanese Yen and bears interest based on the Uncollateralized Overnight Call Rate plus an applicable margin which averaged 0.7% per annum as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014. This loan matures on May&nbsp;10, 2017.&#160; As of both December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, CCJ had 450 million Japanese Yen or $3.7 million outstanding.&#160; The outstanding borrowings are shown as long-term debt within the consolidated balance sheets.&#160; Borrowings and repayments are presented on a gross basis within the Company&#146;s consolidated statements of cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Japanese Working Capital Loan provides for borrowings up to 1.5 billion Japanese Yen, and bears interest based on the Short-term Prime Rate, which was 1.475% as of December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
	&#160; During the first quarter of 2015, the maturity date of the Japanese Working Capital Loan was extended to March&nbsp;31, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
	Borrowings and repayments under the Japanese Working Capital Loan have generally occurred in short term intervals, as needed, in order to ensure adequate liquidity while minimizing outstanding borrowings.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, CCJ had no Japanese Yen outstanding, while as of December&nbsp;31, 2014 CCJ had 100 million Japanese Yen or $0.8 million outstanding.&#160; The outstanding borrowings are shown as short-term debt within the consolidated balance sheets.&#160; Borrowings and repayments are presented on a gross basis within the Company&#146;s consolidated statements of cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On August&nbsp;7, 2015, an amendment was signed to the Uncommitted Revolving Loan Facility Letter (Facility Letter) which was effective as of July&nbsp;19, 2015 and provides for an uncommitted line of credit totaling 5.0 million Renminbi (RMB) or $0.8 million through July&nbsp;19, 2016.&nbsp; The Company is jointly and severally liable as the guarantor under the Facility Letter.&nbsp;
</FONT>
	There were no outstanding borrowings under this facility as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014.

There are no financial covenants and the Company had no outstanding borrowings under the Belgian credit facility as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&#160; Bank guarantees of 0.9 million Euros were issued as of

	4, and 2013 totaled $0.8 million, $0.3 million, and $0.5 million, respectively. These amounts are net of interest costs capitalized of $0.4 million, $0.6 million, and $0.4 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	9. Employee Benefit Plans
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company sponsors defined benefit pension plans covering certain union and non-union employees in the U.S. and Europe.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, all of the plans are frozen to new entrants.&#160; In addition, two of the U.S. plans and one of the European plans do not allow for existing participants to continue to earn benefits under the plans.&#160; The Company uses a measurement date of December&nbsp;31 for all of its pension plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During 2015, the Company incurred a settlement charge of $0.8 million in the plans as a result of employee retirements, and paid $3.8 million from plan assets.&#160; During 2014, the Company offered an opportunity to certain eligible terminated vested participants in two of the U.S. plans to elect a lump sum payment of their respective pension benefits which were paid in the fourth quarter of 2014.&#160; As a result, the Company incurred a settlement charge of $1.0 million in 2014 related to such elections and paid $4.4 million from plan assets.&#160; Also in 2014, the Society of Actuaries released a new mortality table &#151; RP-2014, and a new projection scale &#151; MP-2014.&#160; As a result of these new tables, the Company changed its mortality assumptions for its U.S. plans in 2014.&#160; The Company adopted the new RP-2014 mortality table and a modified version of the new MP-2014 projection scale for the U.S. Qualified Plans which resulted in an increase in the projected benefit obligation of approximately $5.8 million in 2014.&#160; Also in 2014, the projected benefit obligation increased by approximately $12.3 million due to a change in the discount rate assumption.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category consists of growth and value strategies investing primarily in the common stock of large capitalization companies located in the United States.&#160; Growth oriented strategies seek companies within the Russell 1000 Growth Universe with above average earnings, growth, and revenue expectations.&#160; Value oriented strategies seek companies within the Russell 1000 Value Universe that are undervalued relative to their intrinsic value.&#160; These strategies are benchmarked against the Russell 1000 Growth and Value Indices, respectively.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category consists of growth and value strategies investing primarily in the common stock of mid and small capitalization companies located in the United States that are either undervalued relative to their intrinsic value or have above average growth and revenue expectations.&#160; These strategies are benchmarked to the Russell 2500 Growth and Value Indices, respectively.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests in the common stock of primarily U.S. companies across the capitalization spectrum (Large, Mid, and Small Cap) that are undervalued relative to their intrinsic value or represent growth opportunities.&#160; This strategy is benchmarked to the Russell 3000 Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(d)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category consists of international equity securities represented by 21 major MSCI indices from Europe, Australia and Southeast Asia. This strategy is benchmarked to the MSCI EAFE Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(e)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests in all types of capitalization companies operating in global emerging markets outside the United States. The strategy targets broad diversification across various economic sectors in 21 emerging economies.&#160; This category is benchmarked to the MSCI Emerging Markets Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(f)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests primarily in investment grade corporate securities.&#160; This category is benchmarked to the Barclays Aggregate Bond Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(g)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category includes securities and mutual funds which invest in a diversified portfolio of longer duration bonds.&nbsp; The funds typically invest primarily in U.S. investment grade securities.&#160; The portfolio has an average duration that normally varies within two years (plus or minus) of the benchmark.&nbsp; This category is benchmarked to the Barclays Capital Long-Term Government/Credit Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(h)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category includes securities and mutual funds which invest in a diversified portfolio of longer duration foreign bonds.&nbsp; This category is benchmarked to the Barclays Global Aggregate Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(i)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests primarily in mortgage-backed securities which cover the mortgage backed securities component of the Barclays US Aggregate Bond Index.&#160; This category is benchmarked against the Barclays Mortgage-Backed Securities Index.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(j)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This fund invests in assets of commodity linked derivative instruments and fixed income securities.&#160; The fund is benchmarked against the Dow Jones-UBS Commodity Index Total Return.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(k)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This fund normally invests at least 80% of its assets in equity related securities of real estate companies and other real estate securities.&#160; Under normal circumstances, the fund invests in at least three different countries and at least 40% of the total assets are in foreign securities.&#160; This strategy is benchmarked to the Lipper Global Real Estate Funds Average.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company&#146;s investment strategy is to earn the highest possible long-term total rate of return while minimizing the associated risk to ensure the preservation of the plan assets for the provision of benefits to participants and their beneficiaries.&#160; This is accomplished by managing a diversified portfolio of fund styles, asset types, risk characteristics and investment holdings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;

</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:2.5%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</B>

</TD>
<TD WIDTH="28%" COLSPAN="5" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="BORDER:NONE;BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID WINDOWTEXT 1.0PT;PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:28.5%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The discount rates that the Company utilizes for its Qualified Plans to determine pension obligations are based on a review of long-term corporate bonds that receive one of the two highest ratings given by a recognized rating agency.&#160; The expected rate of return on plan assets was determined by the Company based on a review of asset class return expectations, as well as long-term inflation assumptions.&#160; The Company also considered historical returns on asset classes and investment mix.&#160; The expected long-term return on the U.S. Qualified Plans&#146; assets is based on an asset allocation assumption of approximately 40%-50% equity securities, 45%-55% fixed income securities, and 5% with other investments.&#160; The Company also takes into account the effect on its projected returns from any reasonably likely changes in its asset portfolio when applicable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This fund invests in a mix of UK and overseas equity shares, bonds, property and cash. The fund is actively managed against its benchmark of the CAPS Balanced Pooled Fund Median. A prudent approach of diversification by both location and investment type is employed by the fund and both active stock selection and asset allocation are used to add value.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This index fund invests 60% in the UK Equity Index Fund and 40% in overseas index funds. The overseas portion has a target allocation of 14% in North American funds, 14% in European funds (not including the UK), 7% in Japanese funds, and 5% in Pacific Basin funds (not including Japan).
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests in 6 year Fixed Income investments with Delta Lloyd.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(d)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests in the M&amp;G PP Discretionary Fund, the AAA Fixed interest - Over 15 Year Fund, and the M&amp;G PP Long Dates Corporate Bond Fund. These funds, respectively, invest primarily in investment grade corporate bonds, as well as other debt instruments, including higher yielding corporate bonds, government debt, convertible and preferred stocks, money market instruments and equities; and in long-dated sterling denominated AAA-rated corporate bonds, as well as smaller holdings in gilts - both providing a fixed rate of interest.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(e)
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
<I>
	This category invests mainly in long term gilts through the M&amp;G PP Super Long Index Linked Fund and the M&amp;G PP Discretionary Fund.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">

The fund is well diversified investing in the retail, office, and industrial sectors of the market. A small portion of this category is also held in the M&amp;G PP Discretionary Fund.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The expected rate of return on plan assets was determined by the Company based on a review of asset class return expectations as well as long-term inflation assumptions.&#160; Projected returns are based on broad equity and bond indices that the Company uses to benchmark its actual asset portfolio performance based on its targeted portfolio mix of approximately 35%-45% equity securities, 45%-55% fixed income securities and 10%-15% other investments.&#160; The Company also takes into account the effect on its projected returns from any reasonably likely changes in its asset portfolio when applicable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The non-current portion of the U.S. and European pension liabilities of $30.4 million and $31.5 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, is included in accrued pension and other liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Multi-Employer Pension Plan
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In addition to the aforementioned European plans, the Company participates in a multi-employer pension plan in Europe.&#160; This multi-employer plan almost entirely relates to former employees of operations it has divested.&#160; Benefits are distributed by the multi-employer plan.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, the Company has a $0.9 million liability recorded as a component of payroll and benefits payable within its consolidated balance sheets.&#160; Refer to Note 16 for further information related to this multi-employer plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Defined Contribution Plans
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company sponsors a defined contribution plan for certain U.S. employees.&#160; The plan allows for employee contributions, and the Company can make fixed, matching and discretionary contributions to the plan on behalf of its employees.&#160; The Company also makes contributions to the USW 401(k)&nbsp;Plan for certain eligible employees.&#160; Total expenses related to the defined contribution plans were $3.1 million, $2.8 million, and $2.5 million for each of the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	10. Stock Compensation Plans
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had one stock-based compensation plan that was adopted in 2008 and is described below.&#160; The former Employee Stock Option Plan and the Non-Employee Directors&#146; Stock Option Plan (Prior Plans) were terminated and superceded by the 2008 Equity Incentive Plan.&#160; The Prior Plans both had stock-based awards outstanding as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014.&#160; The Prior Plans granted stock options and restricted stock to officers, directors and other key employees of the Company.&#160; The stock options were granted at the fair market value on the grant date, became exercisable no less than six months after granted, and, in general, expire ten years after the date of grant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	2008 Equity Incentive Plan, as amended
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In 2008, the Company adopted an equity incentive plan for eligible employees, service providers, and non-employee directors of the Company and its subsidiaries. In 2014, the Company amended and restated the 2008 Equity Incentive Plan to increase the aggregate number of shares available for issuance from 2,000,000 to 5,000,000, and to extend the term for a period of ten years.&#160; The plan includes a 1,500,000 share fixed sub-limit for the granting of incentive stock options.&#160; The awards may be stock options, restricted stock units, performance units or other stock-based awards.&#160; Stock options may be nonstatutory or incentive.&#160; The exercise price for options and stock appreciation rights shall not be less than the fair market value on the date of grant, except if an incentive stock option is granted to a &#147;10% employee,&#148; as defined by the plan, then the option price may not be less than 110% of such fair market value.&#160; Options and stock appreciation rights may be exercisable commencing with the grant date, and are no longer exercisable after the expiration of seven or ten years from the grant date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Stock-Based Compensation Expense
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The following tables show a summary of the status and activity of stock options for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The expected dividend yield is based on the latest annualized dividend rate and the current market price of the underlying common stock at the date of grant.
</FONT>
	&#160; The expected volatility is based on the historical volatility of the Company&#146;s stock and the implied volatility calculated from traded options on the Company&#146;s stock.&#160; The risk-free interest rates are based on the U.S. Treasury strip rate for the expected life of the option.&#160; For the 2011 through 2015 grants of stock options, the Company used the simplified method for determining the expected life.&#160; This method was used since the Company granted stock options to a different population of its employees, and decreased the term from 10 to 7 years.&#160; As a result of these changes, the Company does not believe that the historical stock option exercise data provides a reasonable basis upon which to estimate the expected life for the 2011 through 2015 grants.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23432_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The total grant date fair value of options vested during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013 was $4.49 per share, $4.80 per share, and $5.32 per share, or $1.5 million, $1.3 million, and $1.0 million, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, the total intrinsic value of stock options exercised (i.e., the difference between the market price at exercise and the price paid by the employee or non-employee directors to exercise the option) was $0.4 million, $1.0 million, and $2.5 million, respectively.&#160; The total amount of cash received from the exercise of options was $1.1 million, $2.2 million, and $4.1 million, for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Restricted and Performance Based Stock Awards
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The grant date fair value of time vested restricted stock awards is the market price of the underlying common stock and is expensed over the vesting period of three years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Performance stock awards, based on Return on Capital (ROC), vest subject to the satisfaction of this performance condition, at the end of a three-year performance period.&#160; The Company&#146;s actual ROC for the performance period is compared to the target set, and the actual award payout is interpolated.&#160; The ROC award can vest at between zero and 200 percent of the target award.&#160; The grant date fair value of the ROC performance stock is the market price of the underlying common stock.&#160; The fair value is expensed on a straight-line basis over the performance period when it is probable that the performance condition will be achieved.&#160;
</FONT>
	No expense was recognized for these awards as it was not considered probable that the performance condition would be achieved.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Performance stock awards, based on Total Stockholder Return (TSR), vest subject to the satisfaction of this market condition, at the end of a three-year performance period.&#160; The Company&#146;s actual TSR for the performance period is compared to the results of its peer companies for the same period with the Company&#146;s relative position in the group determined by percentile rank.&#160; The actual award payout is determined by multiplying the target award by the performance factor percentage based upon the Company&#146;s percentile ranking and can vest at between zero and 200 percent of the target award.&#160; The initial grant date fair value of the TSR performance stock is determined using a Monte Carlo simulation model.&#160; The grant date fair value is expensed on a straight-line basis over the three-year performance period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The following table shows a summary of the status and activity of employee and non-employee directors&#146; nonvested stock awards for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">

</FONT>
</P>

	The weighted-average grant date fair value of restricted stock awards granted during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013 was $21.06 per share, $20.83 per share, and $17.11 per share or $2.4 million, $2.1 million, and $2.2 million, respectively. The total fair value of restricted stock awards vested during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013 was $2.0 million, $1.5 million, and $1.4 million, respectively.

There were no ROC performance stock awards that vested during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.&#160; In addition, the Company did not satisfy the performance condition for the ROC performance stock award that was granted in 2013 and vested in 2016.

</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Total Stock-Based Compensation
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Compensation expense related to all stock-based compensation totaled $3.8 million, $3.7 million, and $3.1 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively, and was recognized as a component of selling, general and administrative expense.&#160; The related income tax benefit was $1.2 million, $1.2 million, and $1.0 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, there was $4.1 million of total future compensation cost related to nonvested share-based compensation arrangements and the weighted-average period over which this cost is expected to be recognized is approximately 1.7 years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	11. Stockholders&#146; Equity
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In November&nbsp;2012, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors authorized an accelerated share repurchase of Company common stock under a share repurchase program (the Program).&#160; On November&nbsp;20, 2012, the Company paid a purchase price of $50 million and initially received 3,276,002 shares upon inception of the Program, for an average purchase price of $15.26 per share. The actual number of shares that the Company repurchased under the Program was determined based on a discount to the arithmetic mean of the volume-weighted average prices (VWAP) of the Company&#146;s common stock for each observation date over the course of the applicable calculation period which ended on September&nbsp;30, 2013.&#160; The actual number of shares repurchased was 340,334 shares less than the number of shares previously delivered, and as a result, the Company sold back that many shares to the counterparty in the form of a private placement of unregistered securities during 2013. The Company&#146;s outstanding common shares used to calculate earnings per share were reduced by the number of repurchased shares pursuant to the Program as they were delivered to the Company, and the $50 million purchase price was recorded as a reduction in stockholders&#146; equity upon its payment.&#160; In 2013, the Company increased its diluted shares outstanding to reflect the 340,334 shares that were sold back in the form of the private placement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In December&nbsp;2013, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors approved an increase in the overall value of shares authorized for repurchase under its Program to $150 million, excluding the November&nbsp;2012 accelerated share repurchase.&#160; Subsequently, the Company initiated an open market share repurchase program whereby 146,800 shares were repurchased in 2013 at an average price per share of $20.37.&#160; During 2014, the Company repurchased an additional 1,930,841 shares at an average price of $20.57 per share.&#160; During 2015, the Company repurchased an additional 2,002,444 shares at an average price of $17.45 per share.&#160; During the period January&nbsp;1, 2016 through February&nbsp;18, 2016, the Company repurchased an additional 518,576 shares at an average price of $15.81 per share.&#160; All of the aforementioned repurchases were funded from operating cash flows, cash on hand, and borrowings and the shares are held as treasury stock.&#160; Subsequent to these repurchases, the Company&#146;s remaining authorization to repurchase its common stock is approximately $64.1 million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On February&nbsp;18, 2015, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors reinstated its common stock dividend program.&#160; Quarterly dividends of $0.05 per share were declared in each of the four quarters for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015.&#160; In addition, on February&nbsp;17, 2016, a common stock dividend of $0.05 per share was declared.&#160; No common stock dividends were declared during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 and 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	63
<A NAME="A15-23432_110K_HTM_PB_63_160340_5335">
</A>
</P>

<TD WIDTH="12%" COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:12.0%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In the fourth quarter of 2015, the Company completed a U.S. research and development tax credit study for the prior years 2012 &#151; 2014.&#160; The Company recognized a benefit of $1.1 million related to the research and development credit.&#160;
</FONT>
	During the second quarter of 2014, the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) completed its joint committee review of the Company&#146;s 2008 amended income tax return.&#160; As a result of the conclusion of this examination, the Company received an income tax refund of $2.5 million including tax and interest which was recorded in other current assets within the Company&#146;s consolidated balance sheet as of December&nbsp;31, 2013.&#160; The Company released net uncertain tax positions including related accrued interest and penalties of $1.4 million as a result of the conclusion of this examination, all of which impacted the Company&#146;s effective tax rate.
</P>

	5, 2014, and 2013, respectively.&#160; No provision has been made for U.S. Federal, state, or additional foreign taxes related to approximately $84.1 million of undistributed earnings of foreign subsidiaries which have been indefinitely reinvested.&#160; Determination of the amount of any such unrecognized deferred income tax liability on this temporary difference is not practicable as such determination involves material uncertainties about the potential extent and timing of any distributions, the availability and complexity of calculating foreign tax credits, and the potential extent and timing of any such distributions, including withholding taxes.

	&nbsp;

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(1)&nbsp;Of the total state tax credit carryforwards, approximately 47% begin to expire in 2023.
</FONT>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(2)&nbsp;Of the total state operating loss-carryforwards, approximately 97% expire in 2020 or later.
</FONT>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(3)&nbsp;Of the total foreign tax operating loss carryforwards, approximately 95% have no expiration.
</FONT>
</I>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	A valuation allowance is established when it is more likely than not that a portion of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&#160; The valuation allowance is adjusted based on the changing facts and circumstances, such as the expected expiration of an operating loss carryforward.&#160; The Company&#146;s valuation allowance as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 of $2.7 million pertained to an uncertainty related to the realization of foreign net operating loss carryforwards, U.S. foreign tax credits, domestic capital loss carryforwards, and state tax credits.&#160; The Company&#146;s valuation allowance as of December&nbsp;31, 2014 of $2.6 million pertained to an uncertainty related to the realization of foreign net operating loss carryforwards, domestic capital loss carryforwards, and state tax credits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, approximately $0.6 million of the $0.8 million, and as of December&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
	4, approximately $1.0 million of the $1.2 million, of unrecognized tax benefits would reduce the Company&#146;s effective tax rate if recognized.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company recognizes accrued interest and penalties related to unrecognized tax benefits in income tax expense.&#160; In 2015, the Company accrued interest and penalties of approximately $33 thousand on current and prior year uncertain tax positions and reversed approximately $0.1 million of interest and penalties due to the expiration of the statute of limitations.&#160; In 2014, the Company accrued interest and penalties of approximately $0.1 million on prior year uncertain tax positions and reversed approximately $0.1 million of interest and penalties due to the expiration of the statute of limitations and approximately $0.6 million due to the settlement of uncertain tax positions.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
	5 and 2014, the amount accrued for the payment of interest and penalties is approximately $0.3 million and $0.3 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Total uncertain tax positions recorded as a component of accrued pension and other liabilities
</FONT>
	within its consolidated balance sheets were approximately $0.9 million and $1.3 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	At this time, the Company believes that it is reasonably possible that approximately $
</FONT>
	0.1 million of the estimated unrecognized tax benefits as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 will be recognized within the next twelve months based on the expiration of statutory review periods all of which will impact the effective tax rate.
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company has entered into leases covering principally office, research and warehouse space, office equipment and vehicles.&#160; Future minimum rental payments required under all operating leases that have remaining noncancelable lease terms in excess of one year are $7.1 million in 201
</FONT>
	6, $6.5 million in 2017, $4.6 million in 2018, $3.3 million in 2019, $2.2 million in 2020, and $20.6 million thereafter.&#160; Total rental expense on all operating leases was $8.9 million, $7.9 million, and $7.6 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	16. Contingencies
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Waterlink
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In conjunction with the February&nbsp;2004 purchase of substantially all of Waterlink Inc.&#146;s (Waterlink) operating assets and the stock of Waterlink&#146;s U.K. subsidiary, environmental studies were performed on Waterlink&#146;s Columbus, Ohio property by environmental consulting firms that provided an identification and characterization of certain areas of contamination.&#160; In addition, these firms identified alternative methods of remediating the property and prepared cost evaluations of the various alternatives.&#160; The Company concluded from the information in the studies that a loss at this property was probable and recorded the liability.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2014, the balance recorded as a component of accounts payable and accrued liabilities was $0.1 million.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the balances recorded as a component of accrued pension and other liabilities were $0.3 million and $0.4 million, respectively.&#160; The Company has determined that there has been insufficient progress to complete the remediation project by the end of 2016.&#160; The Company has further determined that additional site characterization work is needed to establish the next steps.&#160; No estimates regarding the timing or potential cost of these activities can be made until the additional site characterization work is finished.&#160; Planning for the additional characterization work has begun.&#160; Implementation timing will depend on approval by the Ohio Voluntary Action Program administrators.&#160; Liability estimates are based on an evaluation of, among other factors, currently available facts, existing technology, presently enacted laws and regulations, and the remediation experience of experts in groundwater remediation.&#160; It is possible that a further change in the estimate of this obligation will occur as remediation progresses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Carbon Imports
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	General Anti-Dumping Background:
</FONT>
</B>
	&#160; In March&nbsp;2006, the Company and another U.S. producer of activated carbon (collectively, the &#147;Petitioners&#148;) requested that the U.S. Department of Commerce (Commerce Department) investigate unfair pricing of certain thermally activated carbon imported from the People&#146;s Republic of China (China).&#160; In 2007, the Commerce Department found that imports of the subject merchandise from China were being unfairly priced (or &#147;dumped&#148;).&#160;&#160; Following a finding by the U.S. International Trade Commission (ITC) that the domestic industry was injured by unfairly traded imports of activated carbon from China, the Commerce Department issued an anti-dumping order imposing tariffs on Chinese imports to offset the amount of the unfair pricing.&#160; The Commerce Department published the antidumping order in the Federal Register in April&nbsp;2007, and all imports from China remain subject to it.&#160; Importers of subject activated carbon from China are required to make cash deposits of estimated anti-dumping duties at the time the goods are entered into the U.S. customs territory.&#160; Final assessment of duties and duty deposits are subject to revision based on annual retrospective reviews conducted by the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company is a domestic producer, exporter from China (through its wholly-owned subsidiary Calgon Carbon (Tianjin) Co.,&nbsp;Ltd. (Calgon Carbon Tianjin)), and a U.S. importer of the activated carbon that is subject to the anti-dumping order.&#160; As such, the Company&#146;s involvement in the Commerce Department&#146;s proceedings is both as a domestic producer (a &#147;petitioner&#148;) and as a foreign exporter (a &#147;respondent&#148;).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Company&#146;s role as an importer, which has in the past (and may in the future) required it to pay anti-dumping duties, results in a contingent liability related to the final amount of tariffs that are ultimately assessed on the imported product following the Commerce Department&#146;s annual review of relevant shipments and calculation of the anti-dumping duties due.&#160; As a result of proceedings before the Commerce Department that concluded in October&nbsp;2015, the Company is currently required to post a duty of $0.476 per pound when importing activated carbon from Calgon Carbon Tianjin into the U.S.&#160; The impact of the tariffs to the
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	68
<A NAME="A15-23432_110K_HTM_PB_68_155446_5796">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='68',FILE='C:\JMS\C902062\15-23432-1\TASK7798733\23432-1-FV.HTM',USER='C902062',CD='FEB 24 09:29 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage69"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23432_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Company&#146;s financial results was not material for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013.&#160; However, the Company&#146;s
</FONT>
</FONT>
	ultimate assessment rate and future cash deposit rate on such imports could change in the future, as a result of on-going proceedings before the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	As part of its standard process, the Commerce Department conducts annual reviews of sales made to the first unaffiliated U.S. customer, typically over the prior 12-month period.&#160; These reviews will be conducted for at least five years subsequent to a determination by the ITC in February&nbsp;2013, finding that the anti-dumping duty order should remain in effect.&#160; These reviews can result in changes to the anti-dumping tariff rate (either increasing or reducing the rate) applicable to any foreign exporter.&#160; Revision of tariff rates has two effects.&#160; First, it will alter the actual amount of tariffs that U.S. Customs and Border Protection (Customs) will collect for the period reviewed, by either collecting additional duties, plus interest above those deposited with Customs by the U.S. importer at the time of entry or refunding a portion of the duties, plus interest deposited at the time of importation to reflect a decline in the margin of dumping.&#160; Second, the revised rate becomes the cash deposit rate applied to future entries, and can either increase or decrease the amount of duty deposits an importer will be required to post at the time of importation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	There have been eight periods of review since the anti-dumping order was published in 2007.&#160; Periods of Review (POR) I,&nbsp;II,&nbsp;IV and V, related to the periods that ended on March&nbsp;31, 2008, 2009, 2011 and 2012, respectively, are final and not subject to further review or appeal.&#160; A summary of the proceedings in the remaining PORs follows below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Period of Review III:
</FONT>
</B>
	&#160; On October&nbsp;31, 2011, the Commerce Department published the final results of its third annual administrative review, which covers imports that entered the U.S. between April&nbsp;1, 2009 and March&nbsp;31, 2010 (POR III).&#160; Based on the POR III results, the Company&#146;s ongoing duty deposit rate was adjusted to zero.&#160; The Company recorded a receivable of $1.1 million reflecting expected refunds for duty deposits made during POR III as a result of the announced decrease in the POR III assessment rate.&#160; The Commerce Department continued to assign cooperative respondents involved in POR III a deposit rate of $0.127 per pound.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In early December&nbsp;2011, several separate rate respondents appealed the Commerce Department&#146;s final results of POR III.&#160; Following the submission of briefs by the parties, the Court of International Trade (Court) remanded the case to the Commerce Department for further analysis.&#160; On January&nbsp;9, 2014, the Commerce Department filed its remand redetermination with the Court, and continued to calculate a zero duty for the Company during POR III.&#160; In addition, the Commerce Department revised its earlier determination and assigned a zero margin as a separate rate to several Chinese producers/exporters of steam activated carbon to the U.S. that were not subjected to an individual investigation.&#160; The Company contested this aspect of the Commerce Department&#146;s redetermination.&#160; On November&nbsp;24, 2014, the Court affirmed the Commerce Department&#146;s remand determination.&#160; Various parties involved in this review, including the Company, have appealed the decision to the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (Court of Appeals).&#160; Briefing on this appeal was completed in early November&nbsp;2015, and a decision from the Court of Appeals is possible in early 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Period of Review VI:
</FONT>
</B>
	&#160; On November&nbsp;19, 2014, the Commerce Department announced the final margins for its sixth administrative review (POR VI), which covers imports that entered the U.S. between April&nbsp;1, 2012 and March&nbsp;31, 2013.&#160; The Commerce Department calculated a margin of $0.018 per pound for both mandatory and separate rate respondents, and $1.10 per pound for the China wide rate.&#160; Calgon Carbon Tianjin was assigned a margin of $0.018 per pound as it was considered a separate rate respondent.&#160; In December&nbsp;2014, an appeal was commenced challenging the final results of the sixth administrative review.&#160; On January&nbsp;20, 2016, the Court issued a preliminary decision agreeing with the Petitioners&#146; challenge to the Commerce Department&#146;s final margins and directing the agency to reconsider its valuation of a key factor of production.&#160; The Commerce Department&#146;s redetermination is currently due to be filed with the Court in late March&nbsp;2016, and a final decision from the Court is possible in the second or third quarter of 2016.&#160; The impact of the tariffs during this period is not expected to be material to the Company&#146;s financial results.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Period of Review VII:
</FONT>
</B>
	&#160;On April&nbsp;1, 2014, the Commerce Department published a notice allowing parties to request a seventh annual administrative review of the anti-dumping duty order covering the period April&nbsp;1, 2013 through March&nbsp;31, 2014 (POR VII).&#160; The Commerce Department selected two mandatory respondents to be reviewed.&#160; The preliminary results of the Commerce Department&#146;s review of POR VII were announced on April&nbsp;30,&nbsp;2015, with the margins ranging from $0.00 per pound to $0.24 per pound for mandatory respondents, $0.24 per pound for separate rate respondents, and $1.10 per pound for the China wide rate.&#160; Calgon Carbon Tianjin was preliminarily assigned a margin of $0.24 per pound, as it was considered a separate rate respondent.&#160; The Commerce Department announced the final results for POR VII on October&nbsp;5, 2015.&#160; The Commerce Department calculated anti-dumping margins for the mandatory respondents it examined ranging from $0.00 per pound to $0.476 per pound, and it calculated an anti-dumping margin of $0.476 per pound for the separate rate respondents whose shipments of activated carbon to the U.S. were not individually reviewed.&#160; The Company, as a Chinese exporter and a U.S. importer, received the separate rate of $0.476 per pound.&#160; The impact of the revised tariffs to the Company&#146;s financial results is not material. &#160;In October&nbsp;2015, appeals by one of the mandatory respondents and several separate rate respondents were commenced challenging the final results of the seventh administrative review.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	69
<A NAME="A15-23432_110K_HTM_PB_69_155543_2897">
</A>
</P>
